h2: How to Manage Notebook Pages - the User's Guide
p: This is a Guide for managing the notebook pages.

The instrument notebook web service is a diary blog for the instrument. For the users of the instrument, it serves as a text editor for planning, committing and commenting the experiments. For the instrument scientists, it serves as a history journal of the instrument.
Before the experiment starts, the instrument scientists need to use this management page to create a new notebook file. The user starts from an empty page, and gradually add more contents to it.
When a new page is created, the old notebook page is put in the archive list. It's no longer editable (?).

Use the button to create a new notebook page. The old notebook page will be archived. The user can only access the current notebook page. So it hides all archived pages to the user. When clicking on the button, a confirm dialog pops up for you to confirm your action.

Use the button to check the current notebook page. The current notebook page will be loaded to the main area for preview. You can print the page from here. When printing from the browser's menu, it only prints out necessary page area.
Use the button to navigate to the notebook editor page.

In the Archive List, all history notebook pages are listed with their name, which contains a time stamp of when the notebook page was closed. For example, File 'Notebook_150622T142107' was closed on 22 June, 2015.
Click on the file button to load the archived page to the main area.
